transcript.text: Hi everyone welcome to onprint shop.
Today we will see how and when you can use alignment rule.
So the main use of alignment rule is to change the position of any block on the reference of another block.
And the one thing you need to take care while setting up alignment rule is like you have to set the fit method of that particular block as a number fit.
Like here I want to apply the alignment rule on this block.
So I have to set this fit method as a number fit.
The same for another block as well on which I want to apply the alignment rule.
This should be no fit.

So now coming back let us understand how we can apply alignment rule and and when we can apply it in actual case like here in this template we have set one rule in our previous video named dependency rule like if someone doesn't enter this direct number system would hide this D text.
Now the requirement is we want to move this cell number block on the place of this direct number.
So now let us see how we can set this using alignment rule like here we want to 1st move this cell C block.

So I have to go to manage properties, add new rule, select property as alignment rule and the reference block like I want to move this C on the reference of this D block and I want to move this C on the place of this D block and the we can set reference direction like if we want to move it horizontal or vertical.
As of now I want to move it horizontal and save and back.
Let me activate like now cell number I want to move on the place of direct no.
So cell number manage properties.
Here I have already created rule like property should be alignment rule direction reference block is.
I want to move this block on the reference of direct no and I want to move it horizontal so save and back the same I have done for this specs and mobile number as well.
So now let us see the result.
Let me delete this and place this.
Put this as a blank.
Now system would hide the D text and move this cell number on the place of direct number.
So that's it.
This is output.
So that's it.
This is how you can use alignment rules.
Let us know if you have any query questions while creating alignment rules or applying it.
We would be more than happy to assist you.
Bye bye.
